# Function to load and preprocess images
def load_images(image_paths, mask_paths, target_size=(128, 128)):
    images = []
    masks = []
    for img_path, mask_path in tqdm(zip(image_paths, mask_paths)):
        try:
            img = tf.io.read_file(img_path)
            img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3, dtype=tf.uint8)
            img = tf.image.resize(img, target_size)
            mask = tf.io.read_file(mask_path)
            mask = tf.image.decode_image(mask, channels=1, dtype=tf.uint8)
            mask = tf.image.resize(mask, target_size)

            images.append(img)
            masks.append(mask)
        except tf.errors.InvalidArgumentError as e:
            print(f"Error decoding image : {img_path} or {mask_path}")
            continue
    return images, masks

# Load images and masks
images, masks = load_images(image_path, mask_path)
def resize_image(image):
    image = np.squeeze(image)
    image = tf.cast(image, dtype = tf.float32)
    image = image/255.
    image = tf.image.resize(image, (128,128))
    return image
def resize_mask(mask):
    mask = tf.cast(mask, dtype = tf.float32)
    mask = mask/255.
    mask = tf.image.resize(mask, (128,128))
    return mask
X = [resize_image(i) for i in images]
y = [resize_mask(i) for i in masks]
# Split the data into training and validation sets
train_images, val_images, train_masks, val_masks = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2)

# Function to show random samples of images and masks
def show_random_samples(images, masks, num_samples=5):
    indices = np.random.choice(len(images), num_samples, replace=False)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 8))
    for i, idx in enumerate(indices):
        # Display the image
        plt.subplot(num_samples, 2, 2 * i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[idx])
        plt.title('Image')
        plt.axis('off')

        # Display the mask
        plt.subplot(num_samples, 2, 2 * i + 2)
        plt.imshow(masks[idx], cmap='gray')
        plt.title('Mask')
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Show random samples from the validation set
show_random_samples(val_images, val_masks)

# Define the U-Net model
def unet_model(input_size=(128, 128, 3)):
    inputs = keras.Input(input_size)

    # Encoder
    conv1 = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(inputs)
    conv1 = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv1)
    pool1 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(conv1)

    conv2 = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(pool1)
    conv2 = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv2)
    pool2 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(conv2)

    conv3 = layers.Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(pool2)
    conv3 = layers.Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv3)
    pool3 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(conv3)

    # Bottleneck
    conv4 = layers.Conv2D(512, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(pool3)
    conv4 = layers.Conv2D(512, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv4)

    # Decoder
    up5 = layers.Conv2DTranspose(256, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(conv4)
    up5 = layers.concatenate([up5, conv3], axis=3)
    conv5 = layers.Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(up5)
    conv5 = layers.Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv5)

    up6 = layers.Conv2DTranspose(128, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(conv5)
    up6 = layers.concatenate([up6, conv2], axis=3)
    conv6 = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(up6)
    conv6 = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv6)

    up7 = layers.Conv2DTranspose(64, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(conv6)
    up7 = layers.concatenate([up7, conv1], axis=3)
    conv7 = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(up7)
    conv7 = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(conv7)

    # Output
    outputs = layers.Conv2D(1, 1, activation='sigmoid')(conv7)

    model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
    return model

# Create the U-Net model
model = unet_model()

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
train_images_np = np.array(train_images)
train_masks_np = np.array(train_masks)
val_images_np = np.array(val_images)
val_masks_np = np.array(val_masks)

history = model.fit(train_images_np, train_masks_np, epochs=10, validation_data=(val_images_np, val_masks_np))

# Plot training and validation loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Apply threshold to predicted masks

# Invert colors

    plt.title('Original Image')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(num_images_to_predict, 2, 2*i + 2)

    plt.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()

# Threshold value
threshold = 0.5

# Predict masks for some validation images
num_images_to_predict = 1
predicted_masks = model.predict(val_images_np[:num_images_to_predict+1])

# Apply threshold to predicted masks
predicted_masks_binary = (predicted_masks > threshold).astype(np.uint8)

# Define a color for the masks (e.g., red)
mask_color = np.array([0,0,255], dtype=np.uint8)  # ornage color

# Plot original images and predicted masks
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 8))
for i in range(num_images_to_predict):
    # Original image
    original_image = val_images_np[i+1]
    original_image = (original_image * 255).astype(np.uint8)  # Ensure the original image is in uint8 format

    # Predicted mask
    mask = predicted_masks_binary[i+1].reshape(128, 128)

    # Convert binary mask to a colored mask
    colored_mask = np.zeros((*mask.shape, 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    colored_mask[mask == 1] = mask_color

    # Overlay the mask on the original image using alpha blending
    alpha = 0.5
    overlay_image = cv2.addWeighted(original_image, 1, colored_mask, alpha, 0)

    # Plot the original image
    plt.subplot(num_images_to_predict, 2, 2*i + 1)
    plt.imshow(original_image)
    #plt.title('Original Image')
    plt.axis('off')

    # Plot the image with the overlay mask
    plt.subplot(num_images_to_predict, 2, 2*i + 2)
    plt.imshow(overlay_image)
    #plt.title('Image with Predicted Mask')
    plt.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
